Some black playwrights to check out: Pearl Cleage, Suzan-Lori Parks, Lorraine Hansberry, Charles Fuller, Alice Childress...
And school theater clubs don't often attract (or retain) enough black people to put on entire black productions.
Black playwrights are particularly overlooked in canonical literature bc their work is so often so clearly "protest literature."
Maybe Nashville having so many HBCUs leaked into public education bc I see Midwest & NE folks saying they didn't read black lit until later.
Born & raised in Nashville. I was bussed to school to end segregation but black lit was definitely a part of my public education as a child.
I guess I took all that for granted bc seeing some of y'all say you never read black authors until high school or college has me like 😳
My high school was an arts magnet. Some friends performed 'for colored girls...' We went to see an August Wilson play on a field trip.
In 7th grade, my English teacher tried to stop us from reading I Know Why the Caged Bird Sings bc she said it was too graphic. We protested.
We attended summer programs at HBCUs like Fisk and Tennessee State. In 5th or 6th grade, my English class watched Roots.
One of my aunts took me book-shopping one Saturday a month & always steered me toward a black author to include in my purchases.
Luckily, I was exposed to black writers well before high school. Found 'Black Poets' (Dudley Randall) in a breakfront from my great-g'ma.
